, div.Indented\r\n\t{mso-style-name:Indented;\r\n\tmso-style-priority:7;\r\n\tmargin-top:0in;\r\n\tmargin-right:0in;\r\n\tmargin-bottom:0in;\r\n\tmargin-left:9.0pt;\r\n\tmargin-bottom:.0001pt;\r\n\tfont-size:10.0pt;\r\n\tfont-family:"Verdana","sans-serif";}\r\nspan.EmailStyle20\r\n\t{mso-style-type:personal;\r\n\tfont-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";\r\n\tcolor:black;}\r\nspan.EmailStyle21\r\n\t{mso-style-type:personal-compose;}\r\n.MsoChpDefault\r\n\t{mso-style-type:export-only;\r\n\tfont-size:10.0pt;}\r\n@page WordSection1\r\n\t{size:8.5in 11.0in;\r\n\tmargin:1.0in 1.0in 1.0in 1.0in;}\r\ndiv.WordSection1\r\n\t{page:WordSection1;}\r\n--></style><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\r\n<o:shapedefaults v:ext="edit" spidmax="1026" />\r\n</xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\r\n<o:shapelayout v:ext="edit">\r\n<o:idmap v:ext="edit" data="1" />\r\n</o:shapelayout></xml><![endif]--></head><body lang=EN-US link=blue vlink=purple><div class=WordSection1><p class=MsoNormal>C &amp; R Press<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>2013 De Novo Prize for a 1st or 2nd Book of Poetry<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>April 29, 2013<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Hello C &amp; R Press -<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Since my work falls well outside of the mainstream of current American work, I approach publications where I must pay to be considered quite judiciously. I must say I was happy to read that C &amp; R wants poetry that &#8220;threatens our preconceived notions&#8230;&#8221; &#8211; Sounds good to me; I hope your editorial assistants and guest judge share the sentiment.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>At any rate, C &amp; R seems like a good press, with a good heart. So, with that thought, and in that spirit, I''ve attached a PDF document that contains my manuscript <i>The First Book of Muwadi</i> as entry for the 2013 De Novo Prize. As requested in your guidelines, the manuscript does not contain my name.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Some of the pieces from the manuscript have been published in journals, or are coming soon. However, to preserve anonymity, I&#8217;ve removed the Acknowledgments page from the manuscript.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Also, as requested, a brief bio:<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=Indented>Victor David Sandiego lives in the high desert of central México where he walks the cities and mountains, plays drums with jazz combos and in musical / poetry collaborations, writes, and studies. His work appears in various journals and on public radio. His web site is victordavid.com.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Thanks, and of best of effort to you in sorting through what is likely to be a large quantity of excellent entries. If you need any more information from me, please let me know.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Victor David Sandiego<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>99Poets@VictorDavid.com<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>206.317.1345 (U.S. Skype #)<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Manuscript: The First Book of Muwadi<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Attachments:<o:p></o:p></p><p class=Indented>C&amp;R_Press-The First Book of Muwadi-Victor David Sandiego-Manuscript.pdf<o:p></o:p></p><p class=Indented>C&amp;R_Press-The First Book of Muwadi-Victor David Sandiego-CoverLetter.pdf<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>PayPal transaction number: 1XY62010HC523101P<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p></div></body></html>');
INSERT INTO "submission_message" ("id", "entry_id", "submissionbatchid", "outgoing", "sender_name", "sender_email", "recipient_name", "recipient_email", "subject", "display", "sent_date", "received_date", "body_format", "body") VALUES (91, E'00000000FC0A50B868F35745AE9D2EED70629592440C2000', 243, E'0', E'uspoetsinmexico@verizon.net', E'uspoetsinmexico@verizon.net', E'stephanie.s.woodruff@hotmail.com', E'stephanie.s.woodruff@hotmail.com', E'Merida Fellowship Award - Recipient Announcement', E'Merida Fellowship Award - Recipient Announcement', '2012-10-01 18:59:35', '2012-10-01 19:00:59', 2, E'<div style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; COLOR: #000000; FONT-SIZE: 12px"><span style="font-size:12;font-family:arial;color:#000000;"><br /></span>U.S. Poets in Mexico is pleased to announce the recipient of our <span style="font-weight: bold;">2013 Merida Fellowship Award</span>. Judge Kimiko Hahn selected <span style="font-weight: bold;">Emilia Phillips</span>.<br /><div style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; COLOR: #000000; FONT-SIZE: 12px"><div><span style="font-size: small;"><br /><span style="font-size: small;"></span>About Emilia''s poem,&quot;Subject in the Position of the Soldier with No Arms&quot;,&nbsp; Kimiko Hahn commented, &quot;<font class="Apple-style-span"><span><span>The poet of these poems weaves strands of current events with personal concerns.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp; </span>In doing so, the reader is drawn in to the ardor of the first person.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp; </span>The poems move, urging us to care.&quot;<br /><br />Kimiko Hahn also chose two <span style="font-weight: bold;">Honorable Mentions</span>: for <span style="font-weight: bold;">Elizabeth Hoover</span>''s poem &quot;the archive is all in present tense&quot; and <span style="font-weight: bold;">Ryan Black</span>''s poem &quot;Motherless Child&quot;.&nbsp; Honorable Mention recipients will receive a $200 discount on tuition should they decide to participate in our Conference week.<br /><br />Thanks go out to everyone who entered! A total of 66 entries were received. This was by far the strongest group of entrants we have had since inception.&nbsp; <br /><br />Kindest regards,<br /></span></span></font></span></div><div><span style="font-size: small;">&nbsp;</span></div><span><span style="font-size: small;">Sheila Lanham, Director</span><br />U.S. Poets in Mexico<br />P.O. Box 4150<br />Grand Central Station<br />New York, NY 10163<br /><a class="parsedLink" href="http://www.uspoetsinmexico.org" target="_blank">http://www.uspoetsinmexico.org</a></span></div><br /></div>');
INSERT INTO "submission_message" ("id", "entry_id", "submissionbatchid", "outgoing", "sender_name", "sender_email", "recipient_name", "recipient_email", "subject", "display", "sent_date", "received_date", "body_format", "body") VALUES (92, E'00000000FC0A50B868F35745AE9D2EED70629592640E2000', 240, E'0', E'The Labletter', E'thelabletter@labletter.com', E'99poets@VictorDavid.com', E'99poets@VictorDavid.com', E'Must climb his neck, poem by Victor David Sandiego', E'Must climb his neck, poem by Victor David Sandiego', '2012-11-13 13:00:37', '2012-11-13 13:01:21', 2, E'<html style="">\r\n\t<head>\r\n\t\t<title>Must climb his neck, poem by Victor David Sandiego</title>\r\n\t</head>\r\n\t<body>\r\n\t\t<center>\r\n\t\t\t<table border="0" bordercolor="#000000" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse: collapse;" width="573">\r\n\t\t\t\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div style="float: left;">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<img alt="" src="http://www.labletter.com/img/banner_title_monthly.gif" /></div>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div style="float: right;">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<font color="#a0a0a0" face="Arial, sans-serif" size="3">November 2012</font></div>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td width="100%">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<img alt="" src="http://www.labletter.com/img/banner_line.gif" /></td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td width="100%">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div style="margin-top: 10px; padding-left: 30px;">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<font face="Verdana, Arial, sans-serif" size="3">Must climb his neck</font></div>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div style="padding-left: 30px;">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<font face="Verdana, Arial, sans-serif" size="2">from <em>The Second Book of Muwadi</em></font></div>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div style="margin-bottom: 10px; padding-left: 30px;">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<font face="Verdana, Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><em>Victor David Sandiego</em></font><br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<font face="Verdana, Arial, sans-serif" size="2"> </font>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p style="margin-top: 0px;">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<font face="Verdana, Arial, sans-serif" size="2">My death rolled over in bed with a sorrowful face.<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t“Why do you not embrace my torso\x3f” it asked<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tand for a moment<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tI became frozen between worlds.<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tThe babbling street crawled in one ear through the window<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tand heaven descended from the bovada bricks<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tinto the other. Street and heaven clashed behind my eyes<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tand severed my vision.<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tBut I recovered and to my death replied:<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t“It is your neck I love, the rough dusty feel on my fingers<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\twhen I caress the crypt”—<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tand my death merely stared at me,<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tas if I had ordered a coffee in a foreign tongue. </font></p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</div>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td width="100%">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<hr color="#999999" size="1" width="100%" />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</div>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><em>Victor David Sandiego lives in the high desert of central México where he walks the cities, plays drums with jazz combos and in musical/poetry collaborations, writes, and studies. His work appears in various journals and on public radio and he has won a few poetry contests. As in the first volume, </em>The Second Book of Muwadi<em> explores both internal and external conflicts of belief, their imperfect resolutions, and our relationship to an elusive and perhaps illusory redeemer. For more information and to see more of his work, please visit his website, <a href="http://click.icptrack.com/icp/relay.php\x3fr=113598550&msgid=732263&act=W2SL&c=489870&destination=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.victordavid.com">www.victordavid.com</a>.</em> </font></div>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div align="center" style="margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 20px;">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Monthly Notes <em>are presented by</em> The Labletter<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<a href="http://click.icptrack.com/icp/relay.php\x3fr=113598550&msgid=732263&act=W2SL&c=489870&destination=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.labletter.com" target="_blank">www.labletter.com</a> </font></div>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<br />\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t&nbsp;</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t</tbody>\r\n\t\t\t</table>\r\n\t\t\t<p>\r\n\t\t\t\t&nbsp;</p>\r\n\t\t</center>\r\n\t\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">\r\n <tr>\r\n <td width="100%" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n <p style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size:12px; line-height:20px; color:#5e5e5e; margin: 0px 0px 5px;">This message was sent to 99poets@VictorDavid.com from:</p>\r\n <p style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size:12px; line-height:20px; color:#5e5e5e; margin: 0px 0px 5px;">Labletter LLC | 3712 N. Broadway #241 | Chicago, IL 60613</p>\r\n </td>\r\n <td width="2%" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n <p style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size:9px; line-height:13px; color:#5e5e5e;">Email Marketing by\r\n <a href="http://www.icontact.com/a.pl/144186" target="_blank"><img src="http://app.icontact.com/images/icontact_tryFree.gif" alt="iContact - Try It Free!" border="0" /></a></p>\r\n </td>\r\n </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">\r\n\t<tr>\r\n\t\t<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t \t<a href="http://app.icontact.com/icp/mmail-mprofile.pl\x3fr=113598550&l=60937&s=W2SL&m=732263&c=489870" style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica, san-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px; color: #115880; font-weight: bold; text-decoration: none;">\r\n\t\t\t\t\tManage Your Subscription\r\n\t\t\t\t</a>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t</tr>\r\n\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n\t<img src="http://click.icptrack.com/icp/track.php\x3fmsgid=732263&act=W2SL&r=113598550&c=489870" width="1" height="1">\r\n</body>\r\n</html>');
INSERT INTO "submission_message" ("id", "entry_id", "submissionbatchid", "outgoing", "sender_name", "sender_email", "recipient_name", "recipient_email", "subject", "display", "sent_date", "received_date", "body_format", "body") VALUES (93, E'00000000FC0A50B868F35745AE9D2EED7062959244092000', 249, E'1', E'Victor David Sandiego', E'99poets@VictorDavid.com', E'''2012SFPAContest@googlemail.com''', E'2012SFPAContest@googlemail.com', E'SFPA contest submission (Long)', E'SFPA contest submission (Long)', '2012-09-12 14:41:11', '2012-09-12 14:41:00', 1, E'Hello SFPA –\r\n\r\nThe following is an entry for your 2012 Science Fiction Poetry Association Poetry Contest. Category is Long (about 100 lines). I am not an SFPA member.\r\n\r\nThank you.\r\n\r\nVictor David Sandiego\r\n\r\n=================\r\nMy red smoking heart\r\n=================\r\n\r\nI hate to say this – but I live in a Chinese labor camp.\r\n\r\nI hate to say it because I KNOW the Chinese\r\nimprison only flawed, evil persons\r\n(and only the most dreadful go to a camp).\r\n\r\nAfter all, the Chinese are a fair and moderate people.\r\nI must deserve to be here.\r\nI must have committed AN EXTRAORDINARY crime.\r\n\r\n      _I wonder what it was._\r\n\r\nThe sky is the same shade of gray\r\nas the guards.\r\n\r\nThe guards arrange their face\r\nmuscles in the same impenetrable manner as this boulder\r\nI must shatter.\r\n\r\n      _And I imagine:_\r\n\r\nIf I struck these inscrutable faces with this filthy pick\x3f\r\n\r\nOh, there would be only a bit of hard flesh dislodged\r\na grating sound of rusted metal on stone\r\nmaybe a _small_ spark\r\nif I managed to hit an iron bone.\r\n\r\nI don’t dare, of course. I would be impregnated with bullets\r\nand then:\r\ngive birth to a bloody heap of rags.\r\n\r\nNow and then, I wonder\x3f\r\n\r\n      _If That Wouldn’t Be So Bad._\r\n\r\n**\r\n\r\nI was a good child\r\ngrowing up in a household of inexpensive vases.\r\n\r\nMy father was a carpenter and my mother\r\na virgin.\r\n\r\nOf course, she wasn’t _really_ our mother\r\nbut we called her Mamá\r\nand on her birthday brought her bits of lace from the marketplace.\r\n\r\nIt wasn’t until much later\r\n\r\n      _(after the war)_\r\n\r\nthat my virtue began to wobble on its axis\r\nmy rectitude slipped from my chest into my pants\r\nand my wickedness grew a long branch.\r\n\r\nI don’t remember what happened, but I do know\r\neven an impartial judge would hand me this sentence\r\nwith eagerness.\r\n\r\nYou see: I _am_ a criminal child, an assailant of sacrosanct ideals\r\na mass murderer of morals…\r\n\r\nWell, that’s what they tell me anyway, and after this long procession of years\r\nI don’t know how to doubt.\r\n\r\n**\r\n\r\nToday is different though! Today I am going to be free!\r\nA guard has leaned his rifle against a tree!\r\nHe has only his dagger to stab his midday meal!\r\n\r\nTHIS IS MY CHANCE!\r\nto live without these restraints I clench in my red smoking heart\r\nlike an army of shackles.\r\nNow I can return to the life I love!\r\n\r\n      _But he sees my shadow and turns quickly:_\r\n\r\nWith the force of his legs rising from a crouch\r\nand his arm moving upward like a victorious torch\r\nhe PLUNGES his blade directly between my first and my second true ribs\r\ndirectly into the thumping mallet of my heart.\r\n\r\nAnd when he withdraws the dagger, a thin ribbon\r\nof crimson smoke follows it, twisting and growing a little wider\r\nbefore it dissipates in the air.\r\n\r\nAnd I hate to say this – but it isn’t me.\r\nIt isn’t _my_ life that leaps from my red chest.\r\n\r\nIt is a woman I once loved, a single face among millions;\r\nshe entered me\r\n\r\n      _(without warning)_\r\n\r\nand left jagged footprints on my stomach and thighs.');
