l-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''>I am submitting the following pieces for your consideration:<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''>The back of my head<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''>I want a bomb<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''>The dead gods must die<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''>Who calls me one name by war and another by peace<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''>Doing things to her hair<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''>As requested, a brief bio:<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''>Victor David Sandiego lives in the high desert of central México where he walks the cities and mountains, plays drums with jazz combos and in musical / poetry collaborations, writes, and studies. His work appears in various journals and on public radio. His web site is victordavid.com.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''>Thank you. Please let me know if you need any more information<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''>Victor David Sandiego <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''><a href="mailto:99Poets@VictorDavid.com"><span style=''color:#2626FF;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#2626FF;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''>99Poets@VictorDavid.com</span></a><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#262626;mso-style-textfill-fill-alpha:100.0%''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#002060''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><h2>The back of my head<o:p></o:p></h2><p class=MsoNormal>From: <i>The Second Book of Muwadi</i><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''text-align:justify''>One pale morning, roosters and donkeys in my ear, I awoke to discover the back of my head missing from the pillow. I ran through the streets shouting: &#8220;Oh God, give me back my palace of angels!&#8221;. Surely, he had removed the back of my head, my beautiful repository of devotion, because he had judged my wandering wicked, but by my compass, I am on a just shore.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''text-align:justify''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''text-align:justify''>I pounded on doorways to rouse complicit strangers for are we not all a piece of creation&#8217;s heart and liver\x3f They looked at me with smoldering pity, as if I did not know the difference between two devils. Their blindness inflamed me, infected me with an eccentric sickness: I saw the mesquite fingers of God covered with thorns, daring me to climb into his hand.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''text-align:justify''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''text-align:justify''>Not easily fooled, I backed into a wall and raised my arms in crucifixion. &#8220;Seize the rest of me!&#8221; I shouted. &#8220;Without the back of my head, I am but a man!&#8221;<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#002060''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#002060''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><h2>I want a bomb<o:p></o:p></h2><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>real bad<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>oh, just a little one<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>to carry to the park in summer<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>when school is out.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>I want a bomb to call my own<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>take it home<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>in a small wicker basket, give it a blanket<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>and milk.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Everybody else has one<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>or two or three &#8211;<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>they laugh at me.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>I&#8217;d feel like a man washing my prick<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>if I had a little bomb.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>If I had a bomb, I would fondle it, keep it<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>from getting mad<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>bring it news of cheese <o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>and Pakistan.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>A bomb to grow old with<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>give it soft shrapnel to digest<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>read from the book of triggers<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>under the covers<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>watching through window glass<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>red explosions<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>inside dark clouds.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif";color:#002060''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><h2>The dead gods must die<o:p></o:p></h2><p class=MsoNormal>From: <i>The Desert Gardens</i><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''text-align:justify''>When we emerged from the forest and beheld that endless column of towering dead gods trapped in their motionless march over the shallow brown hills, our breath became their plaything to seize with impunity from our lungs. And ours was a deathless parody of life when we stood shock still and horribly shrunken in their transcendent shadows.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''text-align:justify''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''text-align:justify''>Their phlegmatic world had long endured the insidious erosion of time well before we crawled down from our frozen womb onto the flimsy stage of man. Even the smallest thimble of their history was to ours an enormous cauldron.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''text-align:justify''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''text-align:justify''>Yet &#8211; touching the stone toes of these earliest giants and bending the branches in our necks to regard their extinguished stone eyes &#8211; we: who had long wandered among the cold dusk of trees: we who had circled the shadows in the vain determination to recover our autistic humanity understood at last:  we would leave the darkness, follow our own ardent heartbeat &#8211; and let the dead gods dwindle with dignity into dots on the black horizon.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''text-align:justify''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''text-align:justify''><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><h2>Who calls me one name by war and another by peace<o:p></o:p></h2><p class=MsoNormal>From: <i>The Desert Gardens</i><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>There, inside the goblet of your tumbled heart, exists a reason for your crime, some enigmatic collection of souls who torment you.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Those who surface to persecute the weak and infirm, listen. Like summer rain, your days upon the earth seep into a solstice of streams.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Several lifetimes and still your calculations ignore the inherent goodness of men and women, sunflowers, and grapefruit rind. A walled nation is not free.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Too many have known the iron of your arms. Too many have suffered your intoxicated hallucination of glory.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>This garden belongs to anyone who doesn&#8217;t bind their eyes in blindness. These trees offer shelter to all cultures and shades of skin.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>I have labored many stones and shovels to know you, to understand your sad whims. I have walked your wars and slept your peace.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Your impossible vision of supremacy crumbles into grit and gravel. You build your sick houses and desires on sand.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Look at our calm kindness, who trim turbulence from our voices, who reap glad notes from our crops of concertos. Inspect our teeth.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Another profane passage and you wake to your poisonous drumbeat. The chain forged, is broken. Our dreams crawl like mewling cats in sacks from your river.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>God, on the banks, charges by the sacrifice. A lot of stiff sons arrived in a box. An abundance of gullible soldiers died.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Careless incursions you goaded with such haste and hate have reached the top step of your scaffold. We weep only for the humanity you have trampled.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>It is our debris, and we partake of it. On rubble and ash, we breed a new mountain of mornings. This is our blood you seek &#8211; this is our body.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><h2>Doing things to her hair<o:p></o:p></h2><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>When I was little, my mother was ALWAYS: <o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>doing things to her hair.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>At night: when the sky filled with crows<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>she would rinse it clean<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>but: the pillow was unkind to her<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>(or her dreams were unkind to her)<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>And in the morning, soon after breakfast<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>she lined up the bottles on the bathroom counter<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>opened a pack of Winston<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>and went to work.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>The bottles had names<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>beautiful names <o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>that made her feel: BEAUTIFUL.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>They smelled like turpentine<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>beautiful :: turpentine <o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>for shiny and beautiful hair <o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>like turpentine.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>By noon: the TV shows had convinced her:<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=CharacterVoice>she was all knotted up inside<o:p></o:p></p><p class=CharacterVoice>her insides were a tangled ball of twine.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=CharacterVoice><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Her insides were :: inside<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>when they should be :: outside<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>for everyone to see <o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>how beautiful she was <o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>on the INSIDE and the OUTSIDE<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>with her beautiful hair.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>And she would open another pack of Winston<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>wash the Winston smoke from her hair<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>put the turpentine back in her hair<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>rinse the beautiful turpentine out in the sink.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>An ashtray on the bathroom counter <o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>smothered black tobacco ash<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>a dozen dead Winston filters that never had a chance <o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>to live :: in her hair.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Her beautiful shiny hair!<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>it <i>bounced</i> and <i>danced</i> and <i>sang</i><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>a happy bouncy song!<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>that happy bouncy people could hear!<o:p></o:p></p><span style=''font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Verdana","sans-serif";mso-fareast-language:EN-US''><br clear=all style=''page-break-before:always''></span><p class=MsoNormal>By mid afternoon<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>when the dogs stopped snarling:<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>when the mailman arrived: with beautiful circulars <o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>that promised to make my mother&#8217;s insides<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>straighten up and be beautiful:<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>she was all knotted up inside :: again<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>from the turpentine and Winston<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>and her beautiful hair.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>And she would line up the BRUSHES:<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>coarse, medium, fine<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>on the bathroom counter<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>next to the Winston;<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>brush the knotted turpentine from her hair<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>over and over<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>smaller and smaller<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>finer and finer<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>until each strand of beautiful hair was in the right place<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>like :: library books.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Then: she would pick up the phone<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>to see: if anyone was there<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>if anyone could hear her beautiful bouncy hair<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>SINGING.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>She would put down the phone<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>look out the window at the street<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>to see: if anyone was there<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>if anyone could see her beautiful hair<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>DANCING.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>Then she would open the door<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>taste the breeze through the screen<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>blow Winston smoke through the screen<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>and see: if ANYONE was there<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>if anyone could SMELL her hair<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>her beautiful turpentine hair<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>her happy :: shiny :: bouncy :: dancing HAIR.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p></div></body></html>');
