INSERT INTO "submission_message" ("id", "entry_id", "submissionbatchid", "outgoing", "sender_name", "sender_email", "recipient_name", "recipient_email", "subject", "display", "sent_date", "received_date", "body_format", "body") VALUES (140, E'00000000FC0A50B868F35745AE9D2EED7062959264092000', 249, E'1', E'Victor David Sandiego', E'99poets@VictorDavid.com', E'''2012SFPAContest@googlemail.com''', E'2012SFPAContest@googlemail.com', E'SFPA contest submission (Short)', E'SFPA contest submission (Short)', '2012-09-12 14:26:04', '2012-09-12 14:25:00', 1, E'Hello SFPA –\r\n\r\nThe following is an entry for your 2012 Science Fiction Poetry Association Poetry Contest. Category is Short (prose poem, 351 words). I am not an SFPA member.\r\n\r\nThank you.\r\n\r\nVictor David Sandiego\r\n\r\n=================\r\nThe first death of God\r\n=================\r\nHe hadn’t thought to die so imperceptibly. He always imagined he would cross a dark river of mist in a splendid boat, but he rises early as usual, dips bread in his tea, puts on his autumn coat, swings his front door open toward the south, and greets the ambling daylight in the street.\r\n\r\nAt first, he cannot see that he is dead. His town is transformed from one of modest bricks to a metropolis of giant sculptures and statues. He walks down a great boulevard, up wide entrance steps, and enters an echoing hall.\r\n\r\n“God\x3f” he asks – and a voice that took refuge in his mother’s womb answers:\r\n\r\n      _“God. Do as you will.”_\r\n\r\nHe ascends a curving marble staircase until he emerges on a terrace high above the city. A shivering spot of a girl far below catches his eye with her fingers hooked upward and he changes one of her tears into a copper coin and the breeze that bites her bare arms into a sheepskin blanket.\r\n\r\nSatisfied, he sits on the fat stone rail of the terrace for a moment and admires his desires. He looks outward to the fields around the city, sees seven herds of horses mottled on the ground, and he blows a cloud over them that rains a cure on their galloping sickness.\r\n\r\n“God\x3f” he asks – and a voice that ran to the olive orchards with him when he was a boy answers:\r\n\r\n      _“God. Do as you will.”_\r\n\r\nHe looks farther, twists his eyes around the Earth to a town that wears a different shade of skin. A dark green river flows next to it. He stretches his arm and rearranges the river’s unmade bed. The water leaps from its path, rushes through courtyards and flocks of chickens, topples baker’s kilns and sweeps goats into culverts. Men shout curses from rooftops. Apples and the white bellies of snakes float by.\r\n\r\n“God\x3f” he asks – and a damp voice, in the same silent manner of his father, rolls down his cheek and falls past the terrace rail to join the evaporating morning on the distant street.');
INSERT INTO "submission_message" ("id", "entry_id", "submissionbatchid", "outgoing", "sender_name", "sender_email", "recipient_name", "recipient_email", "subject", "display", "sent_date", "received_date", "body_format", "body") VALUES (141, E'00000000FC0A50B868F35745AE9D2EED70629592E4052000', 219, E'1', E'Victor David Sandiego', E'99poets@VictorDavid.com', E'''atlasaarkarts@gmail.com''', E'atlasaarkarts@gmail.com', E'FW: Poetry Submission: Inquiry ', E'FW: Poetry Submission: Inquiry ', '2012-04-19 23:59:41', '2012-04-19 23:59:00', 1, E'Dear Ms. Haas -\r\n\r\nI am disappointed that Atlas (having posted a channel for "inquiries and submissions" on their web site) has apparently decided that the way to respond to a polite and respectful inquiry is to ignore it. My time is valuable too and having been the editor of a poetry journal, I believe in respecting others with a response, no matter which way my thinking goes in regard to their work.\r\n\r\nApparently Atlas does not agree. I could speculate the reasons for your rudeness, but Atlas surely knows them better than me. Also, I prefer to use my time more productively.\r\n\r\nThank you for reading if you have gotten this far.\r\n\r\nVictor David Sandiego\r\n\r\n\r\n-----Original Message-----\r\nFrom: Victor David Sandiego [mailto:99poets@victordavid.com] \r\nSent: Friday, January 06, 2012 9:22 AM\r\nTo: ''atlasaarkarts@gmail.com''\r\nSubject: FW: Poetry Submission: Inquiry \r\n\r\nDear Ms. Haas,\r\n\r\nA quick follow-up to check on the status of my earlier inquiry. I hope you received it. If not, here it is again. Or, please let me know if I should be asking somebody else.\r\n\r\nThank you.\r\n\r\nVictor David Sandiego\r\n\r\n-----Original Message-----\r\nFrom: Victor David Sandiego [mailto:99poets@victordavid.com] \r\nSent: Thursday, December 15, 2011 6:56 PM\r\nTo: ''atlasaarkarts@gmail.com''\r\nSubject: Poetry Submission: Inquiry \r\n\r\nMs. Madeline Haas\r\nEditorial assistant\r\nAtlas / @las\r\nInternational paperback magazine of new writing, art & image\r\n\r\nDecember 15, 2011\r\n\r\nDear Ms. Haas,\r\n\r\nI am writing to inquire about submitting a few of my works to Atlas. I am a poet who works primarily in the realms of the spiritual, mythological and visionary. I have been published in the United States, and am seeking to reach a broader international audience. My work is not necessarily easy, but worth it. For example, the beginning of a recent poem:\r\n\r\nIn the loosely woven moonlight circling\r\nan embryonic Earth\r\nin the immeasurable origin of multitudes\r\nthe earliest canines drooled\r\na bewildered horde\r\nof aboriginal infants from their leering teeth\r\ninto the soft hands of the leather hills.\r\n\r\nI live in the high desert of central México; mail service (at least to my particular callejon) is somewhat unreliable. If I submit by regular mail, I hope that are able to respond via email. Or if there is an alternate means of submitting that is entirely electronic, I would be grateful if you can please let me know.\r\n\r\nThank you in advance for any information that you can help me with. I look forward to your reply.\r\n\r\nVictor David Sandiego\r\n\r\n99poets@VictorDavid.com\r\nwww.VictorDavid.com');
INSERT INTO "submission_message" ("id", "entry_id", "submissionbatchid", "outgoing", "sender_name", "sender_email", "recipient_name", "recipient_email", "subject", "display", "sent_date", "received_date", "body_format", "body") VALUES (142, E'00000000FC0A50B868F35745AE9D2EED70629592C4052000', 230, E'0', E'Slate Poetry Editors', E'editors@slatepoems.com', E'Victor David Sandiego', E'99poets@VictorDavid.com', E'Re: Victor David Sandiego', E'Re: Victor David Sandiego', '2012-05-11 22:17:00', '2012-05-11 22:17:01', 2, E'<html><body><div style="color:#000; background-color:#fff; font-family:times new roman, new york, times, serif;font-size:12pt"><div><span><div class="MsoNoSpacing">Dear Victor David Sandiego,<o:p></o:p></div><div class="MsoNoSpacing"><br></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="MsoNoSpacing"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></div>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:115%;\nfont-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;\nmso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;mso-ansi-language:\nEN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA">Thank you for your\r\npoetry submission. The volume of submissions we receive<br>\r\nmakes it impossible for us to respond to each author personally.<br>\r\n<br>\r\nWe have considered your submission carefully, and regret we didn''t<br>\r\nfind work that''s right for <span style="color:#366388">Slate</span>.<br>\r\n<br>\r\nWe appreciate your interest, and wish you well in placing your work elsewhere.<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<br>\r\nSincerely,<br>\r\n<br>\r\nThe Poetry Editors at Slate</span></span></div><div><br></div>  <div style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: ''times new roman'', ''new york'', times, serif; "> <div style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: ''times new roman'', ''new york'', times, serif; "> <div dir="ltr"> <font size="2" face="Arial"> <hr size="1">  <b><span style="font-weight:bold;">From:</span></b> Victor David Sandiego &lt;99poets@VictorDavid.com&gt;<br> <b><span style="font-weight: bold;">To:</span></b> editors@slatepoems.com <br> <b><span style="font-weight: bold;">Sent:</span></b> Saturday, April 14, 2012 1:00 AM<br> <b><span style="font-weight: bold;">Subject:</span></b> Victor David Sandiego<br> </font> </div> <br>\r\n<meta http-equiv="x-dns-prefetch-control" content="off"><div id="yiv1207907738"><style><!--\n#yiv1207907738  \n _filtered #yiv1207907738 {font-family:Verdana;panose-1:2 11 6 4 3 5 4 4 2 4;}\n#yiv1207907738  \n#yiv1207907738 p.yiv1207907738MsoNormal, #yiv1207907738 li.yiv1207907738MsoNormal, #yiv1207907738 div.yiv1207907738MsoNormal\n\t{margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"sans-serif";}\n#yiv1207907738 a:link, #yiv1207907738 span.yiv1207907738MsoHyperlink\n\t{color:blue;text-decoration:underline;}\n#yiv1207907738 a:visited, #yiv1207907738 span.yiv1207907738MsoHyperlinkFollowed\n\t{color:purple;text-decoration:underline;}\n#yiv1207907738 span.yiv1207907738EmailStyle17\n\t{font-family:"sans-serif";color:windowtext;}\n#yiv1207907738 p.yiv1207907738Indentedjustified, #yiv1207907738 li.yiv1207907738Indentedjustified, #yiv1207907738 div.yiv1207907738Indentedjustified\n\t{margin-top:0in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:0in;margin-left:9.0pt;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"sans-serif";}\n#yiv1207907738 span.yiv1207907738NoSpellCheck\n\t{color:maroon;}\n#yiv1207907738 .yiv1207907738MsoChpDefault\n\t{font-family:"sans-serif";}\n _filtered #yiv1207907738 {margin:1.0in 1.0in 1.0in 1.0in;}\n#yiv1207907738 div.yiv1207907738WordSection1\n\t{}\n--></style><div><div class="yiv1207907738WordSection1"><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal">Slate Poetry</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal">Robert Pinsky, Editor</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal">editors@slatepoems.com</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal"> &nbsp;</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal">Dear Mr. Pinsky,</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal"> &nbsp;</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal">In the attached Word document, I’ve included three poems for your consideration. The first two are from a longer work titled <i>The Second Book of Muwadi</i> and the third is from another longer work, in progress and as yet unnamed. Please consider all as simultaneous submissions.</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal"> &nbsp;</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal">As requested, a brief bio:</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal"> &nbsp;</div><div class="yiv1207907738Indentedjustified">Victor David Sandiego was the winner of\r\n the 1st WordStorm Poetry Competition held on Vancouver Island in British Columbia, a winner of the Jeanne Lohmann Poetry Prize, and the winner of the 2009 Crab Creek Review poetry contest. His work appears in various journals (<i>Floating Bridge Review</i>, <i>Crab Creek Review</i>, <i>Cascade, Prime Number Magazine, Qarrtsiluni, </i>and others<i>)</i> as well as on public radio. As baterista and composer, Victor David performs with others in musical / poetry collaborative settings. He lives in the high desert of central México.</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal"> &nbsp;</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal">Thank you and please let me know if you need more information.</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal"> &nbsp;</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal">Sincerely,</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal"> &nbsp;</div><div class="yiv1207907738MsoNormal">Victor David Sandiego</div></div></div></div><meta http-equiv="x-dns-prefetch-control"\r\n content="on"><br><br> </div> </div>  </div></body></html>');
