-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif"''> DirtychaiMAG [mailto:dirtychaimag@gmail.com] <br><b>Sent:</b> Monday, January 20, 2014 7:31 PM<br><b>To:</b> Victor David Sandiego<br><b>Subject:</b> Re: [Dirty Chai] Metropolis of Crooked Tracks<o:p></o:p></span></p></div></div><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><div><p class=MsoNormal>Victor,&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>Unfortunately, I am not at my desk at the moment, but I will try my best to answer your question about the Author Agreement.<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>The section &quot;Changes to Work&quot; is primarily in place for grammar and spelling edits that need to be done to any pieces. I can assure you that sections similar, if not identical, appear in almost all small press Author Agreements. Here at Dirty Chai, we try to be as open and clear as possible in our agreement language, so that all contributors are able to fully understand the terms. I feel that I should make note that we receive hundreds of submissions every week, and are fortunate enough to choose the work that speaks to us- because the author has perfected the story or poem- and to change a title, or rewrite the work in any way would be unnecessary.<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>That being said, I loved your work and would love to feature it in our upcoming issue-- but only if you feel comfortable with our terms. Your happiness is most important and I, on behalf of Dirty Chai, respect any decision you come to.<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>If you have any other questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to shoot me another email.<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>-Azia DuPont<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p cla