></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>I am very happy to hear you are going to allow your work to appear in Dirty Chai. I loved your style and I think you will enjoy the issue when it is published.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>Happy Tuesday!<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>Azia DuPont<br><br>Sent from my iPhone<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal style=''margin-bottom:12.0pt''><br>On Jan 21, 2014, at 11:05 AM, &quot;Victor David Sandiego&quot; &lt;<a href="mailto:99poets@victordavid.com">99poets@victordavid.com</a>&gt; wrote:<o:p></o:p></p></div><blockquote style=''margin-top:5.0pt;margin-bottom:5.0pt''><div><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";color:#1F497D''>Hello Azia –</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";color:#1F497D''>&nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";color:#1F497D''>Thanks for your response and clarification. With your reply, I understand the section better and trust that you won’t need or want to make any changes. I’ve submitted the Author Agreement form and would like to say thanks again for selecting my work. It’s nice to find a great home for these pieces.</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";color:#1F497D''>&nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";color:#1F497D''>Victor David </span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";color:#1F497D''>&nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></p><div><div style=''border:none;border-top:solid #B5C4DF 1.0pt;padding:3.0pt 0in 0in 0in''><p class=MsoNormal><b><span style=''font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif"''>From:</span></b><span style=''font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif"''> DirtychaiMAG [<a href="mailto:dirtychaimag@gmail.com">mailto:dirtychaimag@gmail.com</a>] <br><b>Sent:</b> Monday, January 20, 2014 7:31 PM<br><b>To:</b> Victor David Sandiego<br><b>Subject:</b> Re: [Dirty Chai] Metropolis of Crooked Tracks</span><o:p></o:p></p></div></div><p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p><div><p class=MsoNormal>Victor,&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>Unfortunately, I am not at my desk at the moment, but I will try my best to answer your question about the Author Agreement.<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>The section &quot;Changes to Work&quot; is primarily in place for grammar and spelling edits that need to be done to any pieces. I can assure you that sections similar, if not identical, appear in almost all small press Author Agreements. Here at Dirty Chai, we try to be as open and clear as possible in our agreement language, so that all contributors are able to fully understand the terms. I feel that I should make note that we receive hundreds of submissions every week, and are fortunate enough to choose the work that speaks to us- because the author has perfected the story or poem- and to change a title, or rewrite the work in any way would be unnecessary.<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>That being said, I loved your work and would love to feature it in our upcoming issue-- but only if you feel comfortable with our terms. Your happiness is most important and I, on behalf of Dirty Chai, respect any decision you come to.<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>If you have any other questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to shoot me another email.<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>-Azia DuPont<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal><br>Sent from my iPhone<o:p></o:p></p></div><div><p class=MsoNormal style=''margin-bottom:12.0pt''><br>On Jan 20, 2014, at 7:09 PM, &quot;Victor David Sandiego&quot; &lt;<a href="mailto:99poets@victordavid.com">99poets@victordavid.com</a>&gt; wrote:<o:p></o:p></p></div><blockquote style=''margin-top:5.0pt;margin-bottom:5.0pt''><div><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Cambria","serif"''>Hello Azia DuPont</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Cambria","serif"''>&nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Cambria","serif"''>Thank you for your note. That’s great that you want publish the two pieces.</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Cambria","serif"''>&nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Cambria","serif"''>I’ve read the Author’s Agreement and am not comfortable with the part titled “Changes To Work”.&nbsp; I can understand that at times an editor wants changes and that publication is contingent upon the author agreeing to those changes. But I’m not willing to agree to the possibility of changes to title and/or text without my approval. Formatting changes I can understand to fit web pages or a particular book size, but this section goes beyond that. </span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Cambria","serif"''>&nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Cambria","serif"''>If you can assure me that in this case there won’t be any alterations to the titles or texts or the two pieces, I can proceed. Thanks for your understanding and for selecting my work for Dirty Chai.</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Cambria","serif"''>&nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Cambria","serif"''>Sincerely</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-family:"Cambria","serif"''>Victor David</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><span style=''font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";color:#1F497D''>&nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal><b><span style=''font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif"''>From:</span></b><span style=''font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Tahoma","sans-serif"''> <a href="mailto:dirtychaimag=gmail.com@email.submittable.com">dirtychaimag=gmail.com@email.submittable.com</a> [<a href="mailto:dirtychaimag=gmail.com@email.submittable.com">mailto:dirtychaimag=gmail.com@email.submittable.com</a>] <b>On Behalf Of </b>Dirty Chai<br><b>Sent:</b> Monday, January 20, 2014 12:03 PM<br><b>To:</b> Victor David Sandiego<br><b>Subject:</b> RE: [Dirty Chai] Metropolis of Crooked Tracks</span><o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p><p class=MsoNormal style=''margin-bottom:12.0pt''>Dear Victor David Sandiego, <br><br>Thank you so much for allowing Dirty Chai to read your work! <br><br>We love AT THE GATE OF MUWADI and FOR THE LOVE OF THESE CREEDS and would be honored to feature them in our e-publication, Dirty Chai: Issue Two: Adventureland. Your piece will also appear on <a href="http://www.dirtychaimag.com">http://www.dirtychaimag.com</a> as part of our online literary content following the publication of the issue. <br><br>Below you will find a link to the Author’s Agreement. Please submit the form at your earliest convenience. Once received, we will prepare your work for publication. If you have any questions, please feel free to contact us. <br><br>Note: your work will not be published without a completed Author''s Agreement. <br><br>Thank you again. <br><br>Sincerely, <br>Azia DuPont <br>Founder &amp; Co. Editor, Dirty Chai <br><br>Link to Author Agreement: <br><a href="http://bit.ly/1gAv2bS">http://bit.ly/1gAv2bS</a> <o:p></o:p></p></div></blockquote></div></blockquote></div></body></html>');
